              <h2>How to use the loan comparison calculator</h2>
              <p>
                This tool lets you compare up to four loans side by side. It
                works for personal loans, auto loans, debt consolidation loans,
                and any standard amortizing loan with fixed payments.
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <strong>Choose the number of loans</strong> you want to
                  compare (2–4).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Select payment frequency</strong> (monthly, bi-weekly,
                  or weekly).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Enter loan details</strong> for each option:
                  <ul>
                    <li>Loan name (e.g., “Bank A personal loan”).</li>
                    <li>Loan amount.</li>
                    <li>Interest rate (nominal APR).</li>
                    <li>Term in years.</li>
                    <li>Optional: upfront fees and recurring monthly fees.</li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                  Click <strong>“Compare loans”</strong> to see payments, total
                  interest, total cost, and effective APR.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h2>Loan payment formula</h2>
              <p>
                For a standard amortizing loan with fixed payments, the payment
                is calculated using:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p class="mb-1"><strong>Payment formula</strong></p>
                <p>Let:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li><code>P</code> = loan amount (principal)</li>
                  <li>
                    <code>r</code> = periodic interest rate (annual rate /
                    payments per year)
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <code>n</code> = total number of payments (years × payments
                    per year)
                  </li>
                </ul>
                <p>Then the payment is:</p>
                <p>
                  \( \text{Payment} = P \times \dfrac{r(1+r)^n}{(1+r)^n - 1} \)
                </p>
                <p class="mt-2">
                  Total interest paid is: \( \text{Total Interest} =
                  \text{Payment} \times n - P \)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>What really matters when comparing loans</h2>
              <p>When you compare loan offers, focus on these key metrics:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Monthly (or periodic) payment</strong> – affects your
                  cash flow and affordability.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Total interest paid</strong> – shows how much you pay
                  the lender for borrowing.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Total cost of the loan</strong> – principal + interest
                  + fees.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Effective APR</strong> – interest plus fees expressed
                  as an annual rate.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                A lower payment does not always mean a cheaper loan. A longer
                term can reduce the payment but increase the total interest
                paid. This calculator highlights both payment size and total
                cost so you can see the trade-offs clearly.
              </p>

              <h2>Comparing loans with different terms and fees</h2>
              <p>
                Lenders often compete using different combinations of rates,
                terms, and fees. For example:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Loan A: lower rate but higher upfront fee.</li>
                <li>Loan B: higher rate but no fee.</li>
                <li>
                  Loan C: longer term with lower payment but higher total
                  interest.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                By entering each offer into this calculator, you can see which
                one has the lowest total cost and how much you save compared
                with the most expensive option.
              </p>

              <h2>Limitations and assumptions</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  The calculator assumes a fixed interest rate and fixed
                  payments over the term.
                </li>
                <li>
                  It does not model variable-rate loans, interest-only periods,
                  or balloon payments.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Effective APR is an approximation based on level payments and
                  the fees you enter.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                For complex loan products (e.g., adjustable-rate mortgages or
                loans with promotional rates), use this tool as a rough guide
                and review the lender’s official APR disclosure.
              </p>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>How do I compare two or more loans fairly?</h3>
              <p>
                Use the same loan amount and term where possible, then compare
                the resulting payment, total interest, and total cost. If the
                terms must differ (for example, one lender only offers 3 years
                and another offers 5 years), focus on total cost and whether the
                higher payment of the shorter loan is affordable for you.
              </p>

              <h3>Is a lower interest rate always better?</h3>
              <p>
                Usually, but not always. A lower rate with very high fees can be
                more expensive overall than a slightly higher rate with no fees.
                That’s why this calculator lets you include both upfront and
                recurring fees and shows an effective APR.
              </p>

              <h3>
                Should I choose the lowest payment or the lowest total cost?
              </h3>
              <p>
                If cash flow is tight, you may prioritize a lower payment even
                if it costs more in total interest. If you can afford higher
                payments, choosing the loan with the lowest total cost will
                usually save you the most money over time.
              </p>

              <h3>What about early repayments or extra payments?</h3>
              <p>
                This version of the calculator assumes you make only the
                scheduled payments. If you plan to make extra payments, the true
                total interest will be lower than shown. Check your loan terms
                for any prepayment penalties before paying off early.
              </p>
